Short answer: yes! 🤩

And just like on Earth it varies wildly. Like Earth, Mars has seasons, strong winds, and clouds, but it also has huge differences. 

Our Mars weather expert José Antonio Rodríguez-Manfredi explains the fascinating phenomena happening on the Red Planet. Now, thanks to the Mars Environmental Dynamics Analyzer instrument on our Perseverance Mars Rover, we're learning even more about Martian meteorology with daily weather reports. 

Credit: NASA

Only once in a blue Moon is our skywatching calendar this busy! Here’s a breakdown of when to look up: 

☄️ Aug. 11 – Enjoy the peak of the Perseid meteor shower around 10 p.m. (22:00) your time, until early morning twilight.

🌌 Aug. 19 – Jupiter will be directly opposite the Sun from Earth.

🌕 Aug. 22 – Gaze at the beautiful full blue moon.

🪐 🔆 All month long, Jupiter and Saturn can be seen from sunset to sunrise, as the pair are at “opposition,” which is when they’re at their biggest and brightest. 

🔭 Who will you go stargazing with? Tag them below! ⬇️

Credit: NASA

⁣
🤩Get excited: it’s one of the best times of the year to enjoy the magic of the Milky Way! If you can find your way to dark skies, our galaxy’s bright, complex core can be seen looking south. 

🌟If you’re looking west, enjoy Venus blazing in the night sky as the “Evening Star” after sunset. 

🔴Each evening this month, Venus and Mars inch closer together, culminating with a close conjunction on July 12. 

😌Remember, turn an eye to the sky this month! 

Credit: NASA

This month has many treats for you stargazers! Here’s a breakdown of when and where to look up: ⁣
⁣
😎June 10 – A partial solar eclipse visible in the Northeast U.S., Eastern Canada, and Northern Europe. ⁣
☀️June 20 – The Summer solstice in the Northern Hemisphere at 11:32 p.m. EDT.⁣
🍓June 24 – A “Strawberry” Full Moon. ⁣
🔭All month – The constellation Scorpius visible in the evening southern sky, and Saturn and Jupiter visible in the south at dawn. ⁣
⁣
And for more Jupiter excitement in June, @NASASolarSystem’s Juno spacecraft is making its next close flyby over Jupiter on June 8th, and this time it will also make a low-altitude flyby over the planet-sized, icy moon Ganymede on June 7th. ⁣
⁣
Credit: NASA⁣
⁣

node.text:
Two bold new @NASASolarSystem missions, DAVINCI+ and VERITAS, will become the first NASA spacecraft in 30 years to visit this hot, hellish, unforgiving world.⁣
⁣
They'll seek to understand how Venus became an inferno-like world, when it has so many other characteristics similar to Earth. ⁣
⁣
DAVINCI+, a descent sphere that will plunge through Venus' thick atmosphere, will measure its composition to understand how it formed and evolved, and determine whether the planet ever had an ocean. It'll also take the first high resolution pictures of the unique geological features on Venus known as “tesserae,” which may be comparable to Earth’s continents.⁣
⁣
VERITAS, an orbiter, will map Venus’ surface to determine the planet’s geologic history and understand why it developed so differently than Earth. It will chart surface elevations over nearly the entire planet to create 3D reconstructions of topography and confirm whether processes such as plate tectonics and volcanism are still active on Venus.⁣
⁣
Credit: NASA⁣ 360
⁣

60 years ago today, astronaut Alan Shepard became the first American to travel in space, climbing some 116 miles (188 km) above Earth's surface, taking space exploration to new heights for the United States!Because of the monumental success of Shepard’s 15-minute flight powered by a Redstone rocket, we proved that we could successfully send humans to space.  Three weeks later, President John F. Kennedy committed the United States to achieving a lunar landing before the end of the decade. ✏️ Quiz time: Astronaut Alan Shepard made it to the Moon later on in his career on which Apollo mission?
A) Apollo 10B) Apollo 12C) Apollo 14Credit:  NASA#NASA #Astronaut #LightThisCandle #Exploration #Galaxy #ReachForTheStars #GameChanger #LevelUp

🔭 In the middle of the month, there's a chance to see all of our solar system's rocky inner planets on the western horizon.

🗓️ Mark your calendars for the May 26 supermoon total eclipse! Over several hours, the Moon will pass through Earth's shadow, causing it to darken and usually become reddish in color. The Moon is also near its closest point to Earth in its orbit, often called a "supermoon."

Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech

node.text:
Skygazers, keep your eyes peeled to the skies this month for beautiful views. ⁣
⁣
🔭 First – Jupiter and Saturn line up with the Moon for a perfect family photo on April 6. Look for them low in the southeast during the hour before sunrise. ⁣
⁣
😍 Next – shift your gaze to the East all month to see the rosy arch known as the Belt of Venus at sunset. ⁣
⁣
Want more? April is also the perfect month to see the constellation Leo light up the night sky in the hours after sunset! ⁣
⁣
Credit: NASA ⁣
⁣

For over 8 minutes today, the core stage of the largest rocket element we've ever built fired its four RS-25 engines - just like it will during @NASAArtemis launches to the Moon. ⁣

An impressive perspective. 😎 

This photo shows off the booster for the Atlas V - part of the @ULALaunch rocket set to launch the #Landsat 9 satellite later this month from Vandenberg Space Force Base in California. Landsat 9 will continue the nearly 50-year legacy of previous Landsat missions of monitoring Earth's changing land and water resources from orbit. 

The satellite will carry two instruments: the Operational Land Imager 2, which collects images of Earth’s landscapes in visible, near infrared and shortwave infrared light, and the Thermal Infrared Sensor 2, which measures the temperature of land surfaces.

Like its predecessors, Landsat 9 is a joint mission with @USGSLandSat.

Credit: NASA

node.text:
High-fives all around! ✋ 

Last week, our Perseverance rover collected the first sample of Martian rock, a core slightly thicker than a pencil from Jezero Crater. This core sample, taken from a rock nicknamed “Rochette,” is the first of many samples from the Mars landscape scientifically identified and selected to return to Earth for closer study. 

They will be safely stored in airtight titanium sample tubes for retrieval. Together with the @EuropeanSpaceAgency, we are planning a series of future missions to return these Martian samples of rock and regolith to Earth. 

Astrobiology, the search for signs of ancient microbial life on other planets, is a key element of our Perseverance mission. In addition to collecting valuable information about the Red Planet’s geology and past climate, Perseverance will help pave the way for human exploration of the Mars. 

Credit: @NASAJPL

La dolce vita 📸⁣

@Astro_Kimbrough captured this photo of southern Italy and Sicily looking out the windows of the cupola on the International Space Station (@ISS). Sicily is the largest Mediterranean island and sits just off the ‘toe’ of Italy’s easily recognizable ‘boot’ shape.⁣

Similar to the window that looks out to the neighborhood, the cupola lets crew members keep an eye on activities outside the ISS such as robotic activities, the approach of vehicles, and spacewalks. But most of all, the six sides of windows and a direct nadir viewing window provide spectacular views of Earth and celestial objects – it’s arguably the best seat in the house.

node.text:
These stars may be young but they're mighty. 💪 

Sometimes, they expel narrow jets of highly charged gas at hundreds of miles per second. When these streams of gas collide with surrounding clouds of gas and dust, these energetic collisions create stunning objects like the one pictured, known as a Herbig-Haro object.

Herbig-Haro objects can be difficult to observe because their surrounding dust and gas absorb visible light. @NASAHubble Space Telescope’s Wide Field Camera 3 takes images at wavelengths outside a range detected by human eyes. Because of Hubble’s ability to observe at infrared wavelengths – where observations are not as affected by gas and dust – observing rare celestial phenomenon like Herbig-Haro objects is made possible!

Credit: @EuropeanSpaceAgency/Hubble & NASA, B. Nisini

#NASA #HubbleFriday #Space #Astronomy
Catch a glimpse of planet Mercury and look for the bright stars Altair and Arcturus. At only 37 light-years from our solar system, Arcturus is the brightest star in the northern sky!

node.text:
Cue the lights! 🤩Colorful blue lights dance across the Earth’s atmosphere in a rare sight captured by @EuropeanSpaceAgency’s @Thom_Astro aboard the International Space Station. Incoming energy and particles from the sun interacting with Earth’s magnetic field causing bursts of light and color across the magnetosphere. In a glowing aurora, we see billions of these individual collisions of energy lighting up the sky – a breathtaking phenomenon that can also be observed from space. The colors of an aurora can vary depending on which gas is excited and how much energy is being exchanged, and in this case, nitrogen produces the beautiful blue light display.

Credit: ESA
#ESA #SpaceStation #SpaceWeather #BlueAurora

A satellite perspective of the power and scale of Hurricane Ida making landfall on Earth’s surface. Captured via our Worldview tool.⁣
⁣
Forces of nature like tropical storms and hurricanes can devastate communities and reshape landscapes. Hurricane Katrina’s powerful effects left a lasting impact on the city of New Orleans, and 16 years later the city once again braces for Ida’s torrential rains and indomitable winds.⁣
⁣
NASA observations, tracking and modeling of hurricanes utilizing satellite images and data contribute to an improved understanding of both the mysteries and effects of natural disasters to help scientists and citizens better prepare and respond.⁣
⁣
Credit: NASA⁣
 ⁣
#HurricaneIda #NASA #NewOrleans #SatelliteImage #Worldview #EarthData
